The main results of the My High School Portal are: 
- Information provided to pupils and parents, in particular about the current offer in secondary education (schools, educational profiles, capacities, etc.); 
- Facilitated procedure of final exam and enrolment process for pupils and parents; 
- Digital monitoring and implementation of the final exam and entry exams and enrolment in high school; 

- An overview of the pupils’ results (their achievements during schooling, entry exams). 
For enrolment in the school year of 2022/2023, on the administration portal My High School, the basic data is recorded for 1,817 schools, the basic data on 66,076 pupils of the final grade of elementary schooling is recorded. Through public  Portal, 7,993 applications submitted by parents are recorded for taking entry exams. 58,873 wish lists for enrolment are submitted and 12,831 applications are submitted and used for pupils’ enrolment.

-	increased institutional capacity of central and local authorities, human resource equipped with the necessary skills to work as sustainable development experts; 
-	improved inter-institutional coordination to support evidence-based decision making;  
-	increased degree of transparency and comparability of company data on sustainable development, environment, social and personnel, respect for human rights, combating corruption and bribery.

Novelty:
The automatic renewal of the Citizen's Card for people over 25 is an innovative project because 

- It is the public administration that takes the initiative for the renewal of the identification document from the age of 25; 
- It reuses the citizens' data available to the public administration; 
- It eliminates the need to travel to the services; 
- Its success factor is interoperability; 
- It is simple, convenient, and without unnecessary bureaucracy; 
- It ensures the rapid renewal of the identification document, essential to the citizen's relationship with the authorities and other entities, and also allows authentication and digital signature.

Impact & Results:
Highlights: 
- The marked reduction in the waiting time and service time of the face-to-face channel, with a consequent reduction and/or even elimination of queues. Since the service became available, it was possible to remove from the in-person counters more than 3.3 million attendances; 
- Channeling IRN employees assigned to handling renewal requests to other tasks and functions, thus allowing for a more efficient management of human resources;  
- Save citizens time and costs, estimating a popup of more than 5 million hours; 
- Great coverage of the measure: between 150 thousand and 200 thousand citizen cards expire every month 
- Between May 5, 2021 and October 5, 2022 more than 1.8 million automatic renewal PIN letters were sent out and the adhesion rate exceeds 70%.

Description:
A lot of innovative activities are carried out by Dutch and other governments. Unfortunately, the impact is limited. Innovations are stand alone projects, not implemented or scalable within primary processes. This reference model supports the implementation of an innovation management system for governments. As such, it makes it possible for governments to develop the ability to respond faster to change and come up with alternative ways of working managing all the activities, procedures and systems that contribute to making it easier, faster and more effective to innovate. 

To support the implementation and application of innovation management, the Ministry provides:
- Innovation Maturity Scan: an online tool that quickly gives a picture of the maturity of the organization's innovation strength. Can be conducted as a self-scan or guided by a certified consultant;
- Innovation Management System for Government Professional training: a special program for government officials designed and conducted in collaboration with the Total Innovation Management Foundation. Certified professionals work as consultants or within their own organizations;
- Innovation Project Roadmap: a thoughtful approach developed for the central government in collaboration with the Center for Innovation at Leiden University. This approach is supported by a comprehensive set of canvases, to be used in workshops and work sessions.

The innovation management model provides the criteria for setting up one's own innovation management system within an organization. Each element of the model addresses the basic requirements essential for implementing innovation in an integrated approach in relation to the organization's objectives. The model provides input to the organization and the processes to be worked out around innovation. It is the first of its kind because of the possibility to start in an accessible way with an Innovation Maturity Scan developed specifically for the government and afterwards to carry out or take a thorough and structured assessment in the full breadth or in parts that can lead to a qualitative assessment of the innovation capability and the corresponding advice.

The New York City Automated Decision Systems Task Force (ADS Task Force) was established by Local Law 49 of 2018 and was tasked with recommending a process for reviewing the City’s use of automated decision systems (more commonly known as algorithms). Because many City agencies and offices use algorithms to aid their decision-making, and because automated decision systems are becoming more prevalent in all fields, the City is examining ways to ensure these systems align with the goal of making New York City a fairer and more equitable place.

 Local Law 49 of 2018 requires the Task Force to write a set of recommendations that address the following:
- A procedure for impacted individuals to request information on decisions involving automated decision systems;
- A procedure for the City to determine any disproportionate impact on protected categories of persons;
- A procedure for addressing any individual instances of “harm” if a system disproportionately impacts protected categories of persons;
- Feasibility analysis of archiving agency systems and its associated data;
- A process for publicly disclosing information about agency systems; and
- Criteria for identifying which systems should be subject to one or more of the above.

The first of its kind in the country, the Task Force was chaired by Jeff Thamkittikasem, Director of the Mayor’s Office of Operations, and co-chaired by Kelly Jin, Chief Analytics Officer and Director of the Mayor’s Office of Data Analytics, and Brittny Saunders, Deputy Commissioner of Strategic Initiatives at the NYC Commission on Human Rights. Task Force members included representatives from various government agencies and offices as well as partners from the private sector, nonprofit, advocacy, and research communities.

Novelty:
The decree framework is significantly innovative in that it provides a set of performance indicators defined as feasible, relevant, comparable, and capable of driving change in corporate gender equality policies. 

To this end, six strategic assessment areas are identified: 
- culture and strategy; 
- governance;
- human resource (Hr) management processes; 
- opportunities for growth and inclusion of women in business;
- ender pay equity; 
- parental protection and work-life balance.

Each area is marked by percentage weight, for a total of 100, which contributes to the measurement of the organization's current level and future improvement.

Description:
The objectives are: qualification of human resources in IT, applied research, and development of innovative IT solutions for the TST. This is an innovation, as it proposes a model of innovation in the public sector, besides enabling academia to get in touch with the real problems of institutions.

Residency programs in Information Technology (IT) are developed all over the country aiming at training and inserting professionals in the market. The development of Information Technology is a current demand in both public and private institutions, and they lack skilled professionals, but the search for these professionals has been a great challenge for the institutions due to the lack of these professionals in the market.

In this sense, the Residency Program in Information Technology is an important stimulus to innovation, because it inserts the residents (students) in real environments and projects of organizations that have demands/problems in the technological area, while promoting the training of these residents, in a lato sensu post-graduation level. Thus, the Superior Labor Court brought to the institution a model of open innovation through the Residency Program in Information Technology promoted by the Metrópole Digital Institute of the Federal University of Rio Grande do Norte. 

The Residency in Information Technology is a model of open innovation for the jurisdictional sector because:
1) It promotes training of resident students at a lato sensu postgraduate level;
2) It allows the insertion and immersion of the resident students in the environment of the Superior Labor Court, linking theory and practice in the educational process;
3) It brings innovation methodologies and techniques, such as design thinking, user experience and triple track agile in the software development process;
4) Will develop innovative solutions in information technology through real projects applied to the demands of the TST, which meet the demands of users.

In this sense, the Residency Program in Information Technology represents an important mechanism for promoting innovation, since it provides an environment of academic training linked to practice.

Impact & Results:
1) the introduction of a model of open innovation for the Court aiming at the development of innovative solutions; 
2) the possibility of promoting reflection and adaptation of the internal structure, of the information technology unit of the Court, to better support the partnership established with the University; 
3) the establishment and strengthening of partnerships with internal units of the Superior Labor Court itself; 
4) the possibility of applying several approaches such as design thinking, user experience, design sprint, branding, accessibility, among others that raise the level of internal knowledge about and benefits of use for end users; 
5) the possibility of using a technological tool by the lawyers who perform the oral support procedures in the trials of cases of the Superior Labor Court, in order to contribute.

Description:
The Innovation Laboratory of the State of Santa Catarina - Nidus, implemented the Open Innovation Program, in which a process of mapping a challenge faced by the public agencies of Santa Catarina is applied. These entities, which seek Nidus' help, are able to extract a diagnosis of the causes, impacts, sectors, people affected, and variables involved (time, money, technical capacity, technologies involved, etc) that underlie the problem in question. After this diagnosis is made, the real challenge is made public, so that the entire innovation ecosystem can present different options for solutions.

1) The public organs of Santa Catarina bid products/services more worried about complying with the purchasing bureaucracy than in really understanding the problem experienced;
 2) These agencies think that a "system" will solve their problems, when they are unaware of or do not seek to know the other market options and do not communicate between sectors;
 3) The agencies usually suffer an inefficient allocation of resources due to the focus on an isolated procurement.

Today, in 2022, the numbers have exceeded all previous estimates, and now, in September, the number of challenges mapped and prototyped has exceeded, by almost 6 times the initial value, comprising a total of 64 challenges between those finalized and those in progress (prototyping phase), plus 6 challenges in benchmarking, elaboration, etc. 

In general terms, among all the bodies and challenges met by Nidus, besides the quantitative ones achieved, the biggest gains are the systemic and subjective ones. There was a profound improvement in communication, planning, in the process of hiring demands, as well as in the encouragement of employees, collaborators and managers to talk about problems and see opportunities in them.

Impact & Results:
Some significant results include:
- Sending messages to 900 thousand students with overdue debts. In this audience, there was a 73% increase in renegotiations of the Student Financing Fund (FIES), when compared to a non-notified control group; 
- It is estimated that R$1.2 billion were renegotiated more just because the messages were sent. This estimate was made by comparing the renegotiation rate and the renegotiated amount between the notified group and the control group; 
- Sending messages to more than 3.5 million small business owners encouraging them to join the Rescheduling Program for the Payment of Debts within the scope of Simples Nacional (RELP). In this public, the renegotiation rate was 167% higher than in the control group.
- The project is monitored by receiving and analyzing reports that statistically show the quantitative results for each type of message sent, including the control groups.

To date, the IDF has received 1,800 applications and has selected 40 innovative projects. 80% of them are located in an African country, particularly in West Africa. The sectors financed are varied: health, agriculture and food security, education, employment, governance.

Half of the projects funded involve NGOs, 10 involve universities, 7 involve companies, and 4 involve public entities. The projects were all evaluated on the basis of the three criteria developed by the IDF:
- Impact on improving the lives of people living in poverty (or a clear strategy to generate it/them), and clear strategy to rigorously evaluate it;
- The ability of a development innovation to demonstrate more impact per euro than the status quo or alternatives;
- The ability of an innovation to be replicated and deployed quickly or efficiently to reach very large numbers of beneficiaries.

Novelty:
1. For the first time in the area of Justice, the responsibility for executing projects with EU funding is associated with training on how to induce innovation and change necessary for this purpose;  
2. Designed according to the real challenges in the Justice area which need, e.g. to incorporate emerging technologies to manage information and their transparency;  
3. Changes the paradigm of the project cycle in the public sector: from an approach in which the public bodies are mere executors without being involved in their design, to a paradigm of internalization of competencies and project ownership, being committed to the entire project life cycle;  
4. An innovative training method which involves the combination of strategic planning and immersive sessions, with elements of practical application throug group projects and collaboration experiences

Description:
The Intravitreal Injections Clinic project aims to focus care delivery on the patient, defining its own circuit according to clinical protocols and optimizing patient flow, reducing waiting times, managing more efficiently the human resources and equipment available at the Centro Hospitalar Universitário de Lisboa Central (CHULC).

The target audience of this project are adult patients who undergo intravitreal injections (due to degenerative diseases of the macula or retinal vascular diseases) at the S. José Hospital Complex. As a general objective, this project aims to optimize the provision of care to patients with eye-related diseases who benefit from intravitreal injections, providing high standards of treatment and greater convenience for the user. Specifically, the project aims to:
- Improve the service provided to users;
- Significantly reduce the number of trips to the hospital;
- Generate a high level of satisfaction from users and family members/caregivers;
- Contribute to a greater efficiency of material and human resources;
- To increase the quality of the health care provided. 

With the implementation of the Clinic in 4 to 5 attendances, it is possible to ensure the provision of complete care to these users, which also translated into a reduction of transportation costs, whether for the user, family members or hospital and thus we also expect to impact in a better quality of life. The implementation of the project began with the re-qualification of the existing space at H.S. José used by Ophthalmology, the reorganization of human resources and equipment and the definition of circuits using a flowchart with all the stages of patient care by a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, orthoptists, technical assistants and operational assistants.

LIPOR has set up a Purchasing Centre, which is voluntarily adhered to by its Associated Municipalities and other regional public entities. Its main objective is to enter into Framework Agreements that allow, on the one hand, to increase bargaining power and obtain financial gains, namely through price reduction through the scale effect and, on the other hand, to significantly reduce administrative costs and the potential litigation associated with procedures.

The constitution of LIPOR's Purchasing Centre, as an innovative differential, intends to:
- Establish the purchasing and sourcing strategy and policies for the previously determined categories of goods and services, bearing in mind the environmental, social and economic sustainability policies, using sustainability and Circular Economy criteria; 
- Promote and ensure the aggregation of purchasing needs of the contracting entities covered, including the consolidation of needs planning, analysis, normalization and standardization of specifications of products and services to be purchased 
- Estimate the value of the potential savings to be obtained through the aggregation of the purchasing needs of the contracting entities covered; 
- Conduct negotiation processes, with respect to the categories of products and services defined as transversal and proceed, when applicable, with the management of the respective contracts and relationships with suppliers; 
- Monitor the performance and assess the impact (savings) of the centralized negotiation processes developed by CC-LIPOR;
- Promoting the use of CC-LIPOR's services among the contracting entities covered; 
- Support the procurement areas of the adjudicating entities covered that intend to develop municipal negotiation processes (not transversal), as well as make available the existing technological negotiation platforms.

Novelty:
Being the first digital service beyond urban janitorial developed together with Colab in 1 year of partnership, adding even more value to the user of the platform.  

Being the 1st scheduling service implemented by Colab's own system; 
- The service's formative methodology and improvements through Service Design and User Experience (UX) methodologies, an innovative aspect for the body of servers; 
- With the initiative, we are exploring a new methodology of cross-engagement in Colab. With the launch of the service, it was possible to increase the user base by 2,077 users in only 3 days of the service's release. With a larger user base, it is possible to stimulate the population to participate in public consultations, knowledge days related to the sustainable development goals, and to stimulate participation in collaborative urban cleaning, among other possibilities.

Digital public services models for Italian municipalities are based on four fundamental innovative aspects:
1) a user-centered design approach, which has placed citizens needs at the heart of all the digital transformation processes of Italian public administrations;
2) the extreme flexibility guaranteed by the design components (patterns) of both the web pages and the service models, which allows an inner consistency in terms of design and user experience, while giving individual administrations the possibility of customizing the model according to their needs;
3) the strong scalability of the solutions, which can be used by a wide range of administrations (from municipalities with less than 2,500 inhabitants to those with over 500,000) to potentially digitize the whole range of public services offered to their citizens;
4) a full compliance with the national legal framework, including key aspects such as the requirements on accessibility standards.

Impact & Results:
-Decrease in the time spent on students' attendance;
-Improvement in the content offered by the teacher.
-Improvement in the learning process of the students, who can have a more inclusive and quality class.

